  'Philosophy & Ethics': [
    Word(word: 'Philosophy', definition: 'The study of the fundamental nature of knowledge, reality, and existence.', example: 'She specialized in metaphysics within philosophy.'),
    Word(word: 'Ethics', definition: 'Moral principles that govern a person\'s behavior or the conducting of an activity.', example: 'Business ethics address moral dilemmas in the workplace.'),
    Word(word: 'Morality', definition: 'A particular set of beliefs or principles regarding right and wrong behavior.', example: 'His personal morality guided his difficult decision.'),
    Word(word: 'Axiology', definition: 'The philosophical study of value, including the nature of value and valuation.', example: 'Axiology explores the differences between the good and the beautiful.'),
    Word(word: 'Metaphysics', definition: 'The branch of philosophy that deals with the first principles of things, including abstract concepts such as being, knowing, substance, cause, identity, time, and space.', example: 'He wrote his dissertation on the metaphysics of time.'),
    Word(word: 'Epistemology', definition: 'The theory of knowledge, especially with regard to its methods, validity, and scope.', example: 'Epistemology questions how we know what we claim to know.'),
    Word(word: 'Logic', definition: 'The study of the principles of correct reasoning.', example: 'The debate hinged on the logical coherence of their arguments.'),
    Word(word: 'Axiom', definition: 'A statement or proposition which is regarded as being established, accepted, or self-evidently true.', example: 'The entire proof starts from this fundamental axiom.'),
    Word(word: 'Proposition', definition: 'A statement that can be judged as true or false.', example: 'The proposition that all humans are rational beings is debatable.'),
    Word(word: 'Argument', definition: 'A set of reasons or a course of reasoning presented to persuade others that an action or idea is right or wrong.', example: 'His argument contained several structural flaws.'),
    Word(word: 'Premise', definition: 'A previous statement or proposition from which another is inferred or follows as a conclusion.', example: 'The conclusion is invalid because the initial premise was false.'),
    Word(word: 'Conclusion', definition: 'A judgment or decision reached by reasoning.', example: 'The conclusion logically followed from the established premises.'),
    Word(word: 'Validity', definition: 'The quality of being logically or factually sound; correctness of reasoning.', example: 'The argument was invalid because the structure was unsound.'),
    Word(word: 'Soundness', definition: 'The quality of an argument being both valid and having all true premises.', example: 'A sound argument must be both logically valid and factually true.'),
    Word(word: 'Deduction', definition: 'Reasoning from the general to the particular; applying a general rule to a specific case.', example: 'His deduction about the hidden motive was brilliant.'),
    Word(word: 'Induction', definition: 'Reasoning from specific observations to broader generalizations.', example: 'We used induction to form a general rule based on the observed instances.'),
    Word(word: 'Fallacy', definition: 'A mistaken belief, especially one based on unsound argument; a flaw in reasoning.', example: 'Citing an irrelevant authority is a common fallacy.'),
    Word(word: 'Paradox', definition: 'A seemingly absurd or self-contradictory statement or proposition that when investigated or explained may prove to be well-founded or true.', example: 'The liar\'s paradox challenges the very nature of truth.'),
    Word(word: 'Skepticism', definition: 'A philosophical stance of doubting the accepted opinion or beliefs.', example: 'A healthy dose of skepticism is necessary in scientific inquiry.'),
    Word(word: 'Rationalism', definition: 'The theory that reason, as opposed to experience, is the foundation of certainty in knowledge.', example: 'Descartes is often associated with rationalism.'),
    Word(word: 'Empiricism', definition: 'The theory that all knowledge is derived from sense-experience.', example: 'The scientific method is largely based on empiricism.'),
    Word(word: 'A Priori', definition: 'Knowledge or justification that is independent of experience (known through reason alone).', example: 'Mathematical truths are considered a priori knowledge.'),
    Word(word: 'A Posteriori', definition: 'Knowledge or justification that depends on experience or empirical evidence.', example: 'Knowledge of the world’s current temperature is a posteriori.'),
    Word(word: 'Subjectivism', definition: 'The philosophical position that knowledge, truth, or morality is relative to the individual.', example: 'Extreme subjectivism denies any universal moral truths.'),
    Word(word: 'Objectivism', definition: 'The philosophical position that reality exists independently of the mind.', example: 'Objectivism suggests moral facts exist outside of human opinion.'),
    Word(word: 'Deontology', definition: 'An ethical theory holding that certain actions are intrinsically right or wrong, regardless of their consequences.', example: 'Deontology argues that lying is always wrong, even to save a life.'),
    Word(word: 'Consequentialism', definition: 'An ethical theory stating that the consequences of one\'s conduct are the only basis for judging the rightness or wrongness of that conduct.', example: 'Consequentialism focuses purely on the outcomes of actions.'),
    Word(word: 'Utilitarianism', definition: 'A consequentialist theory holding that the best action is the one that maximizes overall happiness or well-being.', example: 'Utilitarianism seeks the greatest good for the greatest number.'),
    Word(word: 'Virtue Ethics', definition: 'An ethical theory that emphasizes the character of the moral agent rather than rules or consequences.', example: 'Virtue ethics asks, "What would a virtuous person do?"'),
    Word(word: 'Egoism', definition: 'An ethical theory that treats self-interest as the foundation of morality.', example: 'Psychological egoism suggests all actions are ultimately self-serving.'),
    Word(word: 'Altruism', definition: 'The belief in or practice of disinterested and selfless concern for the well-being of others.', example: 'He performed the rescue out of pure altruism.'),
    Word(word: 'Hedonism', definition: 'The ethical theory that pleasure (in the sense of the satisfaction of desires) is the highest good and proper aim of human life.', example: 'The ancient school of thought followed strict hedonism.'),
    Word(word: 'Categorical Imperative', definition: 'Kant\'s moral law that is unconditionally binding on all rational agents.', example: 'Universalizing the maxim is the test of the categorical imperative.'),
    Word(word: 'Moral Relativism', definition: 'The view that moral judgments are true or false only relative to some particular standpoint (e.g., that of a culture or historical period).', example: 'Moral relativism suggests no universal moral standards exist.'),
    Word(word: 'Moral Absolutism', definition: 'The ethical view that certain actions are intrinsically right or wrong, regardless of context.', example: 'A belief in moral absolutism contrasts sharply with relativism.'),
    Word(word: 'Moral Dilemma', definition: 'A situation in which a difficult choice has to be made between two or more alternatives, especially ones that are equally undesirable.', example: 'The doctor faced a profound moral dilemma.'),
    Word(word: 'Normative Ethics', definition: 'The branch of ethics concerned with establishing how things should or ought to be, how to value them, which actions are right or wrong, and what kind of people we ought to be.', example: 'Deontology is a major theory within normative ethics.'),
    Word(word: 'Descriptive Ethics', definition: 'The empirical investigation of people\'s moral beliefs and practices.', example: 'Descriptive ethics surveys what people actually believe is right or wrong.'),
    Word(word: 'Applied Ethics', definition: 'The practical application of moral theories and principles to real-world issues.', example: 'Bioethics is a major field within applied ethics.'),
    Word(word: 'Justice', definition: 'Fairness in the way people are treated.', example: 'The concept of distributive justice is often debated in political philosophy.'),
    Word(word: 'Rights', definition: 'A moral or legal entitlement to have or do something.', example: 'Natural rights are considered inherent and inalienable.'),
    Word(word: 'Meta-ethics', definition: 'The branch of ethics that studies the meaning of ethical language and the metaphysical status of moral facts.', example: 'Meta-ethics deals with whether moral truths exist.'),
    Word(word: 'Moral Realism', definition: 'The meta-ethical view that there are objective moral truths that exist independently of human opinion.', example: 'Moral realism suggests that morality is discovered, not invented.'),
    Word(word: 'Moral Nihilism', definition: 'The meta-ethical view that nothing is intrinsically moral or immoral.', example: 'His arguments led to the conclusion of moral nihilism.'),
    Word(word: 'Emotivism', definition: 'The meta-ethical view that moral statements are merely expressions of the speaker\'s feelings.', example: 'Emotivism interprets "murder is wrong" as "Boo to murder!"'),
    Word(word: 'Cognitivism', definition: 'The view that moral statements express beliefs that are capable of being true or false.', example: 'Cognitivism stands in contrast to non-cognitivism like emotivism.'),
    Word(word: 'Non-Cognitivism', definition: 'The view that moral statements do not express propositions that can be true or false.', example: 'Non-cognitivism includes emotivism and prescriptivism.'),
    Word(word: 'Good', definition: 'The central object of ethical pursuit; that which is morally desirable.', example: 'What constitutes the ultimate good is a major philosophical question.'),
    Word(word: 'Bad', definition: 'That which is morally undesirable or wrong.', example: 'They agreed that the outcome was clearly bad.'),
    Word(word: 'Right', definition: 'Morally good, justified, or acceptable.', example: 'The action was deemed right based on the deontological rule.'),
    Word(word: 'Wrong', definition: 'Morally bad, improper, or unjust.', example: 'He apologized for doing the wrong thing.'),
    Word(word: 'Bioethics', definition: 'The study of the ethical issues emerging from advances in biology and medicine.', example: 'The ethics board reviewed the bioethics case concerning gene editing.'),
    Word(word: 'Environmental Ethics', definition: 'The moral relationship of human beings to, and also the value and moral status of, the environment and its non-human contents.', example: 'Environmental ethics demands stewardship of natural resources.'),
    Word(word: 'Political Philosophy', definition: 'The study of fundamental questions about the state, government, politics, liberty, justice, and the enforcement of a legal code.', example: 'Plato’s Republic is a foundational text in political philosophy.'),
    Word(word: 'Social Contract', definition: 'An implicit agreement among the members of a society to cooperate for social benefits.', example: 'Hobbes and Locke developed different versions of the social contract theory.'),
    Word(word: 'Autonomy', definition: 'The capacity of an agent to make an informed, uncoerced decision.', example: 'Patient autonomy must be respected in medical decisions.'),
    Word(word: 'Beneficence', definition: 'The principle of acting in the best interest of others.', example: 'The doctor’s primary duty is beneficence toward the patient.'),
    Word(word: 'Non-maleficence', definition: 'The principle of "do no harm".', example: 'The ethical standard requires adherence to non-maleficence.'),
    Word(word: 'Distributive Justice', definition: 'Fair allocation of resources, benefits, and burdens within a society.', example: 'The debate over taxation often centers on distributive justice.'),
    Word(word: 'Paternalism', definition: 'The policy or practice on the part of people in authority of restricting the freedom of those under their charge in their supposed best interest.', example: 'Medical paternalism is often debated against patient autonomy.'),
    Word(word: 'Whistleblower', definition: 'A person who exposes misconduct, alleged dishonest or illegal activity occurring in a government department, agency, or private enterprise.', example: 'The whistleblower exposed corruption within the agency.'),
    Word(word: 'Accountability', definition: 'The obligation to justify actions or decisions.', example: 'Holding leaders accountable ensures transparency.'),
    Word(word: 'Conscience', definition: 'An inner feeling or voice viewed as acting as a guide to the rightness or wrongness of one\'s behavior.', example: 'He acted against his conscience to secure the deal.'),
    Word(word: 'Integrity', definition: 'The quality of being honest and having strong moral principles.', example: 'She is known for her unwavering integrity in public service.'),
    Word(word: 'Virtue', definition: 'Behavior showing high moral standards.', example: 'Courage is considered a cardinal virtue.'),
    Word(word: 'Vice', definition: 'Immoral or wicked behavior.', example: 'The philosophers examined the nature of various vices.'),
    Word(word: 'Prudence', definition: 'The quality of being cautious and showing good judgment.', example: 'He acted with financial prudence during the recession.'),
    Word(word: 'Temperance', definition: 'Moderation or self-restraint, especially when controlling one\'s emotions or desires.', example: 'Temperance was seen as a key to a good life by Stoics.'),
    Word(word: 'Existentialism', definition: 'A philosophical theory or approach which emphasizes the existence of the individual person as a free and responsible agent determining their own development through acts of the will.', example: 'Existentialism stresses freedom and responsibility.'),
    Word(word: 'Absurdism', definition: 'The philosophical concept of conflict between the human tendency to seek inherent value and meaning in life and the human inability to find any in a purposeless, meaningless, or chaotic universe.', example: 'The main character grappled with absurdism after the loss.'),
