  'Literary Devices': [
    Word(word: 'Literary Device', definition: 'A technique a writer uses to produce a special effect in their writing.', example: 'Figurative language is a broad category of literary devices.'),
    Word(word: 'Figurative Language', definition: 'Language that uses words or expressions with a meaning that is different from the literal interpretation.', example: 'Metaphor and simile are types of figurative language.'),
    Word(word: 'Simile', definition: 'A comparison of one thing with another thing of a different kind, typically using "like" or "as".', example: 'The runner was as fast as a cheetah.'),
    Word(word: 'Metaphor', definition: 'A figure of speech where a word or phrase is applied to an object or action to which it is not literally applicable, without using "like" or "as".', example: 'The politician was a snake in the grass.'),
    Word(word: 'Personification', definition: 'The attribution of human characteristics to something nonhuman, or the representation of an abstract quality in human form.', example: 'The wind whispered secrets through the trees.'),
    Word(word: 'Hyperbole', definition: 'Exaggerated statements or claims not meant to be taken literally.', example: 'I’ve told you a million times to clean your room!'),
    Word(word: 'Understatement', definition: 'The presentation of something as being smaller, worse, or less important than it actually is.', example: 'After the hurricane, saying the town was "a bit damp" was a clear understatement.'),
    Word(word: 'Irony', definition: 'The expression of one\'s meaning by using language that normally signifies the opposite, typically for humorous or emphatic effect.', example: 'The fire station burned down; that is truly ironic.'),
    Word(word: 'Verbal Irony', definition: 'When a speaker says one thing but means the opposite.', example: 'Saying "What lovely weather!" during a massive downpour is verbal irony.'),
    Word(word: 'Situational Irony', definition: 'When the outcome of a situation is the opposite of what was expected.', example: 'The fire chief being afraid of fire is an example of situational irony.'),
    Word(word: 'Dramatic Irony', definition: 'When the audience or reader knows something important that a character in a play or novel does not know.', example: 'The audience knew the killer was in the house, but the main character did not.'),
    Word(word: 'Sarcasm', definition: 'The use of irony to mock or convey contempt.', example: 'His sarcastic reply, "Oh, brilliant idea," showed his true feelings.'),
    Word(word: 'Alliteration', definition: 'The occurrence of the same letter or sound at the beginning of adjacent or closely connected words.', example: 'Peter Piper picked a peck of pickled peppers.'),
    Word(word: 'Assonance', definition: 'The repetition of the sound of a vowel or diphthong in non-rhyming stressed syllables near enough to each other for the echo to be discernible.', example: 'The rain in Spain falls mainly on the plain.'),
    Word(word: 'Consonance', definition: 'The recurrence of similar consonant sounds in close proximity, especially consonants, in a sentence or line of verse.', example: 'Mike likes his new bike.'),
    Word(word: 'Onomatopoeia', definition: 'The formation of a word from a sound associated with what is named.', example: 'The bee went *buzz* past my ear.'),
    Word(word: 'Imagery', definition: 'Visually descriptive or figurative language, especially in a literary work.', example: 'The author used rich imagery to describe the dark forest.'),
    Word(word: 'Sensory Detail', definition: 'Descriptive language that appeals to the five senses (sight, sound, smell, taste, touch).', example: 'The essay was full of sensory details, making the setting vivid.'),
    Word(word: 'Symbolism', definition: 'The use of an object or idea to represent something else, usually a more abstract concept.', example: 'The dove in the poem served as a symbol of peace.'),
    Word(word: 'Allusion', definition: 'An indirect or passing reference to a person, place, event, or literary work outside the text.', example: 'His description of the garden was an allusion to the Garden of Eden.'),
    Word(word: 'Metonymy', definition: 'Referring to a concept by the name of something closely associated with that thing or concept.', example: 'The White House issued a statement (referring to the US Presidency).'),
    Word(word: 'Synecdoche', definition: 'A figure of speech in which a part is made to represent the whole or vice versa.', example: '"All hands on deck" uses hands (part) to mean sailors (whole).'),
    Word(word: 'Paradox', definition: 'A seemingly absurd or self-contradictory statement that, when investigated, may prove to be well-founded or true.', example: 'To save money, we must spend more on advertising; that is the paradox.'),
    Word(word: 'Oxymoron', definition: 'A figure of speech in which apparently contradictory terms appear in conjunction.', example: 'The silence was deafening.'),
    Word(word: 'Juxtaposition', definition: 'The fact of two things being seen or placed close together with contrasting effect.', example: 'The juxtaposition of wealth and poverty highlighted the social divide.'),
    Word(word: 'Idiom', definition: 'A phrase whose meaning cannot be deduced from the individual words.', example: '"Bite the bullet" is an idiom meaning to face a difficult situation.'),
    Word(word: 'Pun (Paronomasia)', definition: 'A joke exploiting the different possible meanings of a word or the fact that there are words that sound alike but have different meanings.', example: 'I’m reading a book on anti-gravity. It’s impossible to put down.'),
    Word(word: 'Analogy', definition: 'A comparison between two things, typically for the purpose of explanation or clarification.', example: 'He used an analogy of a running engine to explain the human heart.'),
    Word(word: 'Extended Metaphor', definition: 'A metaphor that an author develops over several lines, paragraphs, or even an entire work.', example: 'The whole poem developed the central metaphor of life as a journey.'),
    Word(word: 'Apostrophe', definition: 'A direct address to an absent or imaginary person, or to an inanimate object or abstract idea.', example: '"Oh, Death, where is thy sting?" uses apostrophe.'),
    Word(word: 'Euphemism', definition: 'A mild or indirect word or expression substituted for one considered to be too harsh or blunt.', example: '"Passed away" is a euphemism for "died."'),
    Word(word: 'Dysphemism', definition: 'The substitution of a disagreeable or offensive expression for a neutral one.', example: '"Kicked the bucket" is a dysphemism for "died."'),
    Word(word: 'Tone', definition: 'The attitude of a writer toward a subject or an audience.', example: 'The author’s tone was critical yet compassionate.'),
    Word(word: 'Mood', definition: 'The general feeling or atmosphere that a piece of writing evokes in the reader.', example: 'The dark setting created a suspenseful mood.'),
    Word(word: 'Theme', definition: 'The central topic, subject, or message within a narrative.', example: 'The primary theme of the novel was the search for identity.'),
    Word(word: 'Motif', definition: 'A recurring subject, theme, or idea in a literary work.', example: 'The repeated image of broken mirrors served as a motif.'),
    Word(word: 'Foreshadowing', definition: 'A warning or indication of a future event.', example: 'The sudden storm was a piece of foreshadowing for the tragedy to come.'),
    Word(word: 'Flashback', definition: 'A scene set in an earlier time than the main story.', example: 'The main character experienced a vivid flashback to her childhood.'),
    Word(word: 'Pacing', definition: 'The speed at which the story is told, controlled by sentence length and detail.', example: 'The author used short, choppy sentences to speed up the pacing during the chase.'),
    Word(word: 'Stream of Consciousness', definition: 'A narrative style that attempts to depict the fluid, often non-linear flow of a character\'s thoughts.', example: 'The novel utilized stream of consciousness to reveal the protagonist\'s inner turmoil.'),
    Word(word: 'First-Person Narration', definition: 'The story is told by one character using "I".', example: 'The reader is deeply connected to the narrator in this first-person narration.'),
    Word(word: 'Third-Person Omniscient', definition: 'The narrator is outside the story and knows everything about all characters and events.', example: 'The third-person omniscient narrator allowed us to hear every character\'s thoughts.'),
    Word(word: 'Limited Omniscient', definition: 'The narrator is outside the story but only knows the thoughts of one specific character.', example: 'We only saw the events through the hero\'s perspective in this limited omniscient view.'),
    Word(word: 'Didactic', definition: 'Intended to teach, particularly in having moral instruction as an ulterior motive.', example: 'The fable had a clear didactic purpose.'),
    Word(word: 'Pathetic Fallacy', definition: 'The attribution of human emotions and conduct to all aspects of nature (a form of personification).', example: 'The angry storm reflected the hero\'s inner turmoil, an example of pathetic fallacy.'),
    Word(word: 'Aphorism', definition: 'A pithy observation that contains a general truth.', example: '"To err is human" is a famous aphorism.'),
    Word(word: 'Epigram', definition: 'A pithy saying in either verse or prose, often witty or satirical.', example: 'The story ended with a sharp, witty epigram.'),
    Word(word: 'Anaphora', definition: 'The repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses.', example: '"We shall fight on the beaches, we shall fight on the landing grounds..."'),
    Word(word: 'Epistrophe', definition: 'The repetition of a word or phrase at the end of successive clauses.', example: '"...and that government of the people, by the people, for the people, shall not perish from the earth."'),
    Word(word: 'Chiasmus', definition: 'A rhetorical device in which two or more clauses are related to each other through a reversal of structures.', example: 'Ask not what your country can do for you—ask what you can do for your country.'),
    Word(word: 'Rhetorical Question', definition: 'A question asked to make a point rather than to elicit an answer.', example: 'Is the sky blue? That question is rhetorical.'),
    Word(word: 'Denotation', definition: 'The literal, dictionary meaning of a word.', example: 'The denotation of "home" is a dwelling place.'),
    Word(word: 'Connotation', definition: 'The idea or feeling that a word invokes in addition to its literal meaning.', example: '"Home" has a warm, comforting connotation.'),
    Word(word: 'Tone Shift', definition: 'A noticeable change in the author\'s attitude toward the subject within the text.', example: 'The essay moved from an academic tone to a passionate tone, a clear tone shift.'),
    Word(word: 'Vernacular', definition: 'The language or dialect spoken by the ordinary people in a particular country or region.', example: 'The author wrote in the vernacular to make the dialogue authentic.'),
    Word(word: 'Allegory', definition: 'A story, poem, or picture that can be interpreted to reveal a hidden meaning, typically a moral or political one.', example: '"Animal Farm" functions as an allegory for the Russian Revolution.'),
    Word(word: 'Fable', definition: 'A short story, typically with animals as characters, conveying a moral.', example: 'Aesop\'s Fables are well-known examples of this device.'),
    Word(word: 'Moral', definition: 'A lesson or principle conveyed by a story or experience.', example: 'The moral of the story was to always be kind.'),
    Word(word: 'Cliche', definition: 'A phrase or opinion that is overused and betrays a lack of original thought.', example: 'He avoided clichés like "in this day and age."'),
    Word(word: 'In Medias Res', definition: 'The literary technique of starting a narrative in the middle of things.', example: 'The film began *in medias res* with a dramatic chase scene.'),
    Word(word: 'Motif', definition: 'A recurring subject, idea, or symbol in a literary work.', example: 'The repeated image of broken mirrors served as a motif.'),
    Word(word: 'Juxtaposition', definition: 'Placing two contrasting elements side by side to highlight their differences.', example: 'The juxtaposition of the cheerful music and the grim scene was unsettling.')
  ],
  'Policy & Governance': [
    Word(word: 'Policy', definition: 'A definite course or method of action selected from among alternatives and in light of given conditions to guide and determine present and future decisions.', example: 'The government introduced a new foreign trade policy.'),
    Word(word: 'Governance', definition: 'The action or manner of governing a state, organization, or people; the set of institutions and processes that determine how power is exercised.', example: 'Good governance requires transparency and accountability.'),
    Word(word: 'Public Policy', definition: 'A system of laws, regulatory measures, courses of action, and funding priorities concerning a given topic promulgated by a governmental entity.', example: 'Healthcare reform is a major issue in current public policy debates.'),
    Word(word: 'Regulation', definition: 'A rule or directive made and maintained by an authority.', example: 'New environmental regulations were imposed on the manufacturing sector.'),
    Word(word: 'Legislation', definition: 'Laws, collectively; the process of making laws.', example: 'Congress passed the new education legislation after months of debate.'),
    Word(word: 'Statute', definition: 'A written law passed by a legislative body.', example: 'The statute clearly defines the limits of executive power.'),
    Word(word: 'Bureaucracy', definition: 'A system of government in which most of the important decisions are made by state officials rather than by elected representatives.', example: 'The project was delayed due to excessive bureaucracy and red tape.'),
    Word(word: 'Accountability', definition: 'The obligation of an individual or organization to account for its activities, accept responsibility for them, and disclose the results in a transparent manner.', example: 'Lack of accountability led to widespread public mistrust.'),
    Word(word: 'Transparency', definition: 'The quality of being open, honest, and accessible in the conduct of governmental or business affairs.', example: 'The new rule mandates full financial transparency for all public contracts.'),
    Word(word: 'Efficacy', definition: 'The ability to produce a desired or intended result; effectiveness of a policy.', example: 'The study questioned the long-term efficacy of the economic stimulus package.'),
    Word(word: 'Stakeholder', definition: 'An individual, group, or organization that holds an interest or concern in a policy or project.', example: 'All community stakeholders were invited to the public hearing.'),
    Word(word: 'Lobbying', definition: 'The act of attempting to influence decisions made by officials in a government.', example: 'The environmental group engaged in intense lobbying to influence the energy bill.'),
    Word(word: 'Policy Cycle', definition: 'The stages of policy making, typically including agenda setting, formulation, adoption, implementation, and evaluation.', example: 'The committee is currently in the evaluation stage of the policy cycle.'),
    Word(word: 'Agenda Setting', definition: 'The process by which problems or issues become matters of public and governmental attention.', example: 'A major crisis can rapidly drive a topic onto the political agenda setting.'),
    Word(word: 'Policy Implementation', definition: 'The stage of the policy process that involves putting a policy into practice.', example: 'Policy implementation often faces challenges due to bureaucratic resistance.'),
    Word(word: 'Policy Evaluation', definition: 'The process of assessing the policy\'s effects, usually conducted after the policy has been implemented.', example: 'Independent policy evaluation confirmed the negative unintended consequences.'),
    Word(word: 'Fiscal Policy', definition: 'The means by which a government adjusts its spending levels and tax rates to monitor and influence a nation\'s economy.', example: 'The Treasury Department announced a tight fiscal policy to curb inflation.'),
    Word(word: 'Monetary Policy', definition: 'Actions undertaken by a central bank to manipulate the money supply to achieve macroeconomic goals.', example: 'The central bank raised interest rates as a tool of monetary policy.'),
    Word(word: 'Veto', definition: 'A constitutional right to reject a decision or proposal made by a law-making body.', example: 'The President threatened to veto the bill if it was not revised.'),
    Word(word: 'Checks and Balances', definition: 'A system in which the different parts of a government have powers that affect and control the other parts so that no part can become too powerful.', example: 'The system of checks and balances prevents any single branch from dominating.'),
    Word(word: 'Rule of Law', definition: 'The principle that all people and institutions are subject to and accountable to law that is fairly applied and enforced.', example: 'A strong democracy is fundamentally based on the rule of law.'),
    Word(word: 'Public Administration', definition: 'The implementation of government policy and the academic study that prepares civil servants to work in public service.', example: 'She completed her graduate degree in public administration.'),
    Word(word: 'Decentralization', definition: 'The transfer of authority and responsibility from central government to regional or local authorities.', example: 'The new reform calls for greater fiscal decentralization to municipalities.'),
    Word(word: 'Federalism', definition: 'A system of government in which power is divided between a national (federal) government and regional (state) governments.', example: 'The complex division of power is a core feature of federalism.'),
    Word(word: 'Devolution', definition: 'The transfer or delegation of power to a lower level, especially by central government to local or regional administration.', example: 'The parliament voted for the devolution of powers to the regional assembly.'),
    Word(word: 'Civil Society', definition: 'Society considered as a community of citizens linked by common interests and collective activity, independent of government.', example: 'Non-governmental organizations are key actors in civil society.'),
    Word(word: 'Civil Service', definition: 'The permanent professional branches of a government’s administration, excluding military and judicial branches and elected politicians.', example: 'He passed the exam to join the civil service.'),
    Word(word: 'Electoral System', definition: 'The rules that determine how elections and referendums are conducted and how results are determined.', example: 'The debate centers on switching from a simple majority to a proportional electoral system.'),
    Word(word: 'Gerrymandering', definition: 'Manipulating the boundaries of an electoral constituency to favor one party or class.', example: 'Accusations of gerrymandering followed the controversial redrawing of the district lines.'),
    Word(word: 'Sovereignty', definition: 'Supreme and independent authority over a territory or state.', example: 'The treaty acknowledged the nation’s full sovereignty.'),
    Word(word: 'Referendum', definition: 'A general vote by the electorate on a single political question that has been referred to them for a direct decision.', example: 'The government called a referendum on the constitutional amendment.'),
    Word(word: 'Coalition', definition: 'A temporary alliance of political parties forming a government or of states.', example: 'The two smaller parties formed a coalition government.'),
    Word(word: 'Autocracy', definition: 'A system of government by one person with absolute power.', example: 'The country transitioned from a democracy to an autocracy.'),
    Word(word: 'Pluralism', definition: 'A theory that a multitude of groups, not the people as a whole, govern the United States.', example: 'Pluralism suggests that political power is diffused among many groups.'),
    Word(word: 'Citizen Charter', definition: 'A document that sets out the commitment of a government department or agency towards standards of service, information, and accountability.', example: 'The local municipality published its new citizen charter detailing service standards.'),
    Word(word: 'Sunset Clause', definition: 'A provision in a law or regulation that causes it to expire automatically after a certain length of time or on a specific date.', example: 'The new tax incentive included a five-year sunset clause.'),
    Word(word: 'Policy Window', definition: 'A period of time during which a policy change is most likely to occur, often opening after a crisis or election.', example: 'The recent economic downturn created a policy window for banking reform.'),
    Word(word: 'Welfare State', definition: 'A system whereby the state undertakes to protect the health and well-being of its citizens, especially those in financial or social need.', example: 'The country is known for its extensive welfare state programs.'),
    Word(word: 'Public Good', definition: 'A commodity or service that is provided without profit to all members of a society, either by the government or a private organization.', example: 'National defense is the classic example of a public good.'),
    Word(word: 'Cost-Benefit Analysis', definition: 'A systematic process used to calculate and compare the total potential costs and benefits of a proposed policy or project.', example: 'A detailed cost-benefit analysis was required before approving the new infrastructure.'),
    Word(word: 'Public Opinion', definition: 'The collective opinion of many people on some issue, problem, or person of general interest.', example: 'The shift in public opinion forced the legislature to reconsider the law.'),
    Word(word: 'Think Tank', definition: 'An institution, organization, or group of experts providing advice and ideas on political, economic, or social issues.', example: 'The influential think tank released a report criticizing the current tax structure.'),
    Word(word: 'Judicial Review', definition: 'Review by the Supreme Court of the constitutional validity of a legislative act.', example: 'The court exercised judicial review to strike down the unconstitutional law.'),
    Word(word: 'Separation of Powers', definition: 'The vesting of the legislative, executive, and judiciary powers of government in separate bodies.', example: 'The US Constitution is built upon a strong separation of powers.'),
    Word(word: 'Subsidiarity', definition: 'The principle that a central authority should have a subsidiary function, performing only those tasks which cannot be performed effectively at a more immediate or local level.', example: 'The EU operates on the principle of subsidiarity, empowering member states.'),
    Word(word: 'Authoritarianism', definition: 'A political system in which a small group of individuals exercises power over the state without being constitutionally responsible to the public.', example: 'The nation was slowly descending into authoritarianism.'),
    Word(word: 'Democratic Deficit', definition: 'A concern that international or regional organizations lack democratic legitimacy and accountability to the people they affect.', example: 'Critics argue the European Union suffers from a democratic deficit.'),
    Word(word: 'Fiscal Decentralization', definition: 'The transfer of financial resources and responsibilities from the central government to sub-national levels of government.', example: 'Fiscal decentralization aims to improve local resource management.'),
    Word(word: 'Political Economy', definition: 'The study of how political forces and institutions affect the economy, and how economic factors influence political decisions.', example: 'His research focused on the political economy of developing nations.')
  ],
  'Advanced Science': [
